    march_sf_key: "<strong>The key.</strong> No new inventions needed. Politically prioritise and scale existing technologies.",
    march_sf_context: "<strong>The context.</strong> Thirteen ideas from a dinner conversation — sourced and grouped by area of life.",
    march_pull_eyebrow: "Munich · February 2025 · Munich Security Conference",
    march_pull_h4: "What Europe's decision-makers are now demanding out loud.",
    march_pull_li1: "<strong>A European DARPA.</strong> A research agency for AI, drones, cyber and space that puts Europe at the technological front — not eventually, now.",
    march_pull_li2: "<strong>€400 billion already on the table.</strong> The European Stability Mechanism holds €400 billion in unused credit lines. The money for defence and infrastructure exists. What's missing is the political call.",
    march_pull_li3: "<strong>Economic strength is sovereignty.</strong> AI-backed productivity, a completed single market and strategic investment in energy and cloud are not growth themes. They are security policy.",
    march_pull_cite: "Munich Declaration 2025 · munichdeclaration.org",
    march_ch1_title: "Technology & City Life",
    march_ch1_count: "Six Ideas",
    march_idea1_title: "Ground that produces electricity.",
    march_idea1_body: "Piezoelectric paving slabs convert kinetic energy into electricity. A subway station with fifty thousand passengers a day covers its lighting needs this way — no solar, no cable, no new infrastructure. Pavegen runs active installations in London, Paris and Dubai.",
    march_idea2_title: "Paths that light themselves.",
    march_idea2_body: "Studio Roosegaarde built the world's first self-luminous bike path in 2014: 500 metres of paving with no power connection, still operating today. The principle is trivially scalable — every road-surface tender could include it.",
    march_idea3_title: "Shade as infrastructure.",
    march_idea3_body: "In 2023 Seville fitted central streets with shade structures and cooling sprayers. Measured impact: up to five degrees temperature reduction, thirty percent more pedestrian footfall in summer. A template for any Mediterranean city.",
    march_idea3_source: "City of Seville",
    march_idea4_title: "Repair is cheaper than buying new.",
    march_idea4_body: "The EU Right to Repair (April 2024) obliges manufacturers, for the first time, to make spare parts available. Next step: 0 % VAT on repair services, a levy on premature disposal. System design beats appeals.",
    march_idea4_source: "European Commission · Right to Repair",
    march_idea5_title: "Your city pays you a dividend.",
    march_idea5_body: "Cities sell anonymised usage and traffic data to research and companies. Amsterdam is piloting models that distribute the proceeds directly to citizens. Data sovereignty becomes a property right — not just a privacy topic.",
    march_idea6_title: "Buildings that produce food.",
    march_idea6_body: "The BIQ House in Hamburg has run the first urban algae façade at scale since 2013. Biomass for heating and hot water, plus thermal insulation — at costs comparable to conventional façades. Not a prototype: in operation for over ten years.",
    march_ch2_title: "Education & Infrastructure",
    march_ch2_count: "Three Ideas",
    march_idea7_title: "Europe as one single campus.",
    march_idea7_body: "Erasmus+ has given thirteen million people cross-border educational experiences — limited to academic contexts. A universal recognition infrastructure would include vocational training, certificates and practical experience. The train becomes the campus.",
